[2026-03-23 16:00:00] size: 30 | approach: GNFS final CRT attempt | time: 295s (26 deps tried, all fail) | notes: Root ordering inconsistency across CRT primes is the fundamental issue. T(m)^2 = prod(a-b*m) holds for EACH prime individually, but CRT of T(m) values from different primes gives inconsistent result because roots are ordered differently at each prime. This is exactly the Couveignes sign problem. Resolution requires either: (1) Couveignes' p-adic root matching algorithm, (2) Hensel lifting of roots between primes to establish consistent ordering, or (3) Montgomery's algebraic sqrt using number field tower. All are complex multi-page algorithms not trivially implementable.
